Portfolio Optimization under Power Law Returns

Christopher McDonald

26 Aug 2022

Abstract

Monte-Carlo simulation is used to evaluate the distribution of returns for portfolios of investments made at the seed stage. The results confirm that the main benefit of diversification is a higher typical (median) return multiplier. Under the simple model presented, gains from diversification reach diminishing returns at around 1000 firms for “early-exit” strategies, but continue to be substantial beyond this for “late-exit” strategies. Limitations of the model are briefly discussed.

Introduction

Previous work

What is known about the distribution of returns in early-stage venture investments?

The most comprehensive report I could find on this topic is the AngelList report Startup Growth and Venture Returns (Othman, 2019). I will summarise its methods, main results and the conclusions of the author below.

The report uses AngelList’s data on early-stage venture investments to study the distribution of returns for “winning” investments - that is, investments with a return multiplier >1. They study how this distribution varies with 2 factors: (1) the duration of the investment1 and (2) the time that the initial investment is made (e.g. seed stage, series A, series B etc).

The main findings of the report are:

  • A power law (i.e. Pareto) distribution appears to describe the distribution of multipliers well. In particular, it fits the data better than a lognormal distribution.

  • The thickness of the power law tail (determined by its parameter \(\alpha\)) increases with the duration of the investment, and is higher for earlier investments than later ones.

  • In particular, the best fit model for seed stage investments with durations of 5 or more years is a Pareto distribution with a power \(\alpha < 1\)2. This model predicts an unbounded (i.e. infinite) expected multiplier.

  • Startups tend to grow faster (in the sense of having a higher IRR) in their earlier years, and slower in their later years. They provide empirical data to back up this claim.

Based on these results, they make several conclusions:

  • There is a qualitative difference between seed stage investments and later investments; seed stage investments have theoretically infinite multipliers, while the expected multipliers for later stage investments are bounded.

  • Seed stage investors can increase their expected multiplier via diversification (that is, by adding firms to their portfolio).

  • Seed stage investors “should invest in every credible deal”, while later-stage investors “should be more thoughtful and discerning” about their investments.

  • The fundamental nature of startup stock (as an asset class) changes over its lifetime.

Outline

In Theory, I argue that the infinite expected multiplier emphasized by Othman (2019) is misleading. Then in Simulation Study I explain the assumptions, methods and results of the simulation study I performed. Finally in Discussion I briefly discuss my main findings, and list the weaknesses of my model.

Theory

In absence of anything else, physics sets a hard upper limit on the maximum achievable return for any venture3. This tells us that the infinite expected multipliers for seed-stage investments predicted by Othman (2019)’s model is misleading, and should not be taken literally. (Common sense suggests that the real upper limit on multipliers are much lower than the limit set by physics.)

This contradicts Othman (2019)’s claim that seed-stage investments are “qualitatively” (as well as “quantitatively”) different to later-stage investments. Specifically, once you introduce a maximum feasible rate of return, the overall expected multiplier must be finite. However, it is likely that seed-stage investments are still “quantitatively” very different to later-stage investments - for example, they likely offer much higher expected multipliers.

To take into account the existence of a maximum possible return multiplier, Othman (2019)’s model (of Pareto-distributed multipliers) can be modified by introducing a “cut-off” scale \(x_{\text{max}}\). The largest multiplier observed in Othman was 115x, while Peter Thiel is said4 to have achieved a multipler of 2200x on his investment in Facebook (Othman 2020). To be conservative, I will use \(x_{\text{max}} = 10^6\), which corresponds to a $10 billion return on an initial investment of $10,000.

Power law relationships are notoriously hard to fit. Some data may match a power law over a given range, but have tails which drop off faster outside this range. It is hard to distinguish whether this is the case, because (as in this case) you may not have any observations from the range you want to study.

Simulation Study

Othman (2019) provides tentative data on the distribution of returns for individual firms, as a function of the time of investment (e.g. seed stage, series A, …) and the duration of the investment. Here I will use this data along with Monte-Carlo simulation methods to examine the distribution of returns for various portfolios, conditional on certain assumptions about how the portfolios were constructed. This allows me to compare the (theoretical) returns and risk profiles of different portfolios.

These simulations aim to provide a better understanding of what heavy-tailed distributions mean for portfolios of investments, and what an optimal portfolio might look like in this case. While the model presented here is highly simplified, with more realistic assumptions, such simulations could also be used to directly inform decision-making.

In this section, I first discuss the assumptions the model relies on. Following this, I explain briefly how the model was simulated, and then present the results.

Assumptions

The following simplifying assumptions were used:

  • The number of firms that are available to invest in is effectively infinite.

  • The distribution of multipliers for each firm is independent.

  • An equal amount is invested in each firm.

  • There is no marginal cost to investing in an extra firm.

  • Each investment is made at the seed stage.

  • A given firm succeeds (achieves a positive multiplier) with probability \(p = 0.5\). In other words, a firm’s investment multiple \(m\) has \(\mathbb{P}(m \gt 1) = p = \frac{1}{2}\) and \(\mathbb{P}(m \le 1) = 1 - p = \frac{1}{2}\).

  • The multipliers of successful firms are Pareto-distributed (or truncated Pareto -distributed) with scale parameter \(x_{\text{min}} = 1\), and a shape parameter \(\alpha\) which depends on the duration of the investment \(t\) as shown below.

Table 1: Shape parameter \(\alpha\) of the distribution of the multiplier \(m\), as a function of investment duration. Source: Otham (2019), Figure 7.
Investment Duration (years) Shape Parameter \(\alpha\)
1 4.00
2 2.00
3 1.30
4 1.10
5 1.00

8 0.80

Figure 1: Distribution of multipliers for successful (m > 1) firms as a function of investment duration.

  • The multiplier of failing firms is \(\text{Beta}(a, b)\)-distributed with parameters \(a = 3\) and \(b = 1\) (corresponding to a mean of 0.75 and standard deviation of 0.2). This distribution is shown below.

Figure 2: Distribution of multipliers for failing (m < 1) firms. Mean multiplier is shown in red.

  • The distribution of returns is assumed to vary along 3 dimensions:
    1. The number of firms in the portfolio \(k\): either a “small” portfolio (\(k = 10\)), a “medium” portfolio (\(k = 100\)) or a “large” portfolio (\(k = 1000\)).
    2. The duration of the investment \(t\): “early exit” (\(t = 2\) years) or “late exit” (\(t = 8\) years).
    3. The base distribution \(D\): the distribution that multipliers \(m\) are drawn from. Either a standard Pareto distribution (the original model proposed by Othman (2019)), or a truncated Pareto distribution - i.e. a Pareto distribution whose tail is cut off at the maximum scale \(x_{\text{max}} = 10^6\).

Methods

The distribution of the multiplier \(m\) for a given set of parameters was estimated using Monte-Carlo simulation. Specifically, the Monte-Carlo distribution for a given set of parameters (\(k\), \(t\), \(D\)) was calculated as follows:

  • Randomly sample multipliers for each of the \(k\) firms in the portfolio, based on the base distribution \(D\) and the investment duration \(t\).
  • Compute the overall multiplier of the \(k\)-firm portfolio by taking the mean of the multiplier over the firms in the portfolio.
  • Repeat this process \(n\) times to gain \(n\) samples from the distribution of \(k\)-firm portfolio multipliers. Here a relatively large sample size was chosen (\(n = 10,000\)) in order to ensure the tails are adequately sampled.

In this case, the standard deviation mainly measures the thickness of the tail, since it is heavily skewed by outliers. As a result it is not especially useful as a measure of the typical variability you expect when sampling from the distribution. Instead, to measure variability we will use the mean absolute deviation (MAD), which tells us how much a given sample will typically vary from the median.

Monte-Carlo distributions for the multipliers are plotted below.

Figure 3: Monte Carlo distribution of the return multiplier for early exits (t = 2 years).

Figure 4: Monte Carlo distribution of the return multiplier for late exits (t = 8 years).

Some basic observations are:

  • For an investment duration of 2 years - corresponding a power of \(\alpha = 2\) - the results for the Pareto and Truncated Pareto models are practically identical. This is expected, as the models only differ in the tails, which are unlikely to be sampled (given the “lightness” of the tail implied by the value of \(\alpha\)).

  • For this investment duration, the expected multiplier (1.37, 1.17 annualised) is independent of the portfolio size (as expected), and the median multiplier approaches the mean as the portfolio size increases - it is within 2% of the mean multiplier for a portfolio size of \(k = 1000\).

  • For an investment duration of 8 years, corresponding to a power of \(\alpha = 0.8\), the results for the Pareto and Truncated Pareto appear similar, but differ substantially in the tails. As expected, the Truncated Pareto model has a bounded mean (around 70x, or 1.7x annualised), while under the Pareto model the expected multiplier increases dramatically with portfolio size. In contrast, the median multiplier is almost identical between the two models (as expected if they differ only in the tails).

  • While the variability of the multiplier (as measured by the MAD) decreases with portfolio size in the “early-exit” case, variability increases with portfolio size in the “late-exit” case. This can be seen clearly in the figures above. This is because (1) as the portfolio size increases, the chance of seeing outliers from the tail increases; and (2) outliers are extreme enough to substantially skew the average.

Discussion

Contributions

The main contributions of this report are as follows:

  • It empirically confirms that the main benefit of diversification (i.e. a larger portfolio) is in a higher typical (median) multiplier.

  • The model suggests that for “early-exit” strategies, a diversified portfolio gives reduced variability, while for “late-exit” strategies, a diversified portfolio gives increased variability (at least up to portfolio sizes of 1000 firms).

  • The model also suggests that “late-exit” strategies perform better (annualised mean multipliers of 1.7) than “early-exit” strategies (annualised mean multiplier of 1.17) on average.

  • The results give some indication of how much diversification is optimal. Under the simple model above, the gains from diversification begin to reach diminishing returns at around \(k = 1000\) firms in the early-exit case. However in the late-exit case, the gains from diversification continue to be substantial even as the size of the portfolio increases into the thousands of firms.

  • Contrary to Othman (2019), I have argued (in Theory) that there is likely an upper limit on possible returns, which results in a bounded expected multiplier for any given investment.

  • Given finite expected multipliers for investments in individual firms, the expected multiplier of a portfolio is independent of its size - that is, adding firms to a portfolio does not improve your expected multiplier (contrary to what Othman (2019) says). So I argue that, in theory, the only reason to invest in a portfolio (of more than one firm) at all is to improve your risk profile.

  • However, my results provide support for most of Othman (2019)’s practical recommendations. For example, the large gains found from diversification when investing at the seed stage suggest that “invest in every credible deal” is good advice for this stage.

Limitations

There are many weaknesses and limitations of the simulation scheme presented here. Future work could more accurately model reality by taking the following factors into account:

  • Investors have a limited pool of firms they are able to invest in.
  • Firms vary, and investors have different information and beliefs about different firms and their likely returns. (In other words, my model does not take into account an investor’s “edge”.)
  • There are costs (due to research, due diligence etc) to investing in a given firm.
  • Usually there will be multiple investment and exit events for a given firm, rather than just one of each.
    • Investors may make follow-on investments.
    • Investors may adapt their investment strategy as they learn more about the firms they are invested in, and their valuations change.
  • Investors will likely allocate capital unevenly among firms.
  • In reality, the returns of firms will be somewhat correlated rather than independent.
  • The seed stage is not the only stage of investment; further work should look at investments at other stages.
  • It would be useful to see how the distribution of the return multiplier changes over the time.
  • The data source for the model parameters (specifically the power law power \(\alpha\)) needs to be checked for accuracy. For example, no confidence intervals (or other measures of uncertainty) were given in the original report.
